RootCause.name: The default gateway is not available
RootCause.Data: The default gateway is a device that connects a local network or computer to the Internet. A broadband modem or router is usually the default gateway.

Resolution.name: Reset the "%InterfaceName%" adapter
Resolution.Data: This can sometimes resolve an intermittent problem.

Resolution.name: Investigate router or broadband modem issues
Resolution.Data: If you're connected to a hotspot or domain network, contact the network administrator. Otherwise: 1. Unplug or turn off the device. 2. After all the lights on the device are off, wait at least 10 seconds. 3. Turn the device on or plug it back into the power outlet. To restart a router or modem that has a built-in battery, press and quickly release the Reset button.

Resolution.name: Reset the wireless adapter

RootCause.name: There might be a problem with the driver for the %InterfaceName% adapter
RootCause.Data: Windows couldn't automatically bind the IP protocol stack to the network adapter.

Resolution.name: Set up the %FriendlyInterfaceName% adapter
Resolution.Data: Set up the network adapter to communicate with this network. This ensures that both Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4) and Internet Protocol Version 6 (TCP/IPv6) can be used on the network adapter.

Resolution.name: The %FriendlyInterfaceName% adapter is experiencing problems
Resolution.Data: Windows Help and Support can provide more information about resolving driver or hardware issues.

RootCause.name: The Windows wireless service is not running on this computer
RootCause.Data: The Windows wireless service is also called the WLAN Autoconfig service.

Resolution.name: Start the Windows wireless service
Resolution.Data: The Windows wireless service is not running on this computer.

RootCause.name: Your computer does not meet the requirements for DirectAccess
RootCause.Data: Accessing the domain network over DirectAccess requires that your computer be running Windows Server 2008 R2, Windows 7 Enterprise, Windows 7 Ultimate or later. Your computer must be joined to a domain, and your network administrator must have configured DirectAccess for your organization.

Resolution.name: Configure your computer to be compatible with DirectAccess
Resolution.Data:
Make sure your computer is running Windows Server 2008 R2, Windows 7 Enterprise, Windows 7 Ultimate or later. Your computer must be joined to a domain, and your network administrator must have configured DirectAccess for your organization.
If these requirements are met, use an Ethernet, wireless, or VPN connection to connect your computer to the domain. This will update settings controlled by your network administrator.

RootCause.name: The Diagnostics Policy Service is not running
RootCause.Data: Network Diagnostics cannot be run without the Diagnostics Policy Service.

Resolution.name: Start the Diagnostics Policy Service
Resolution.Data: Network Diagnostics requires that the Diagnostics Policy Service be running.

RootCause.name: An Ethernet cable is not properly plugged in or might be broken

Resolution.name: Plug an Ethernet cable into the network adapter "%InterfaceName%"
Resolution.Data: An Ethernet cable looks like a telephone cable but with larger connectors on the ends. Plug this cable into the opening on the back or side of the computer. Make sure the other end of the cable is plugged into the router. If that does not help, try using a different cable.
